            . I am a <rs id="t18320705-284-viclabel1488" type="occupation">milkman and a shoemaker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320705-284-victim2316 t18320705-284-viclabel1488"></join>; I live at <placeName id="t18320705-284-crimeloc1489">Isleworth</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18320705-284-crimeloc1489" type="placeName" value="Isleworth"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18320705-284-crimeloc1489" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320705-284-off1486 t18320705-284-crimeloc1489"></join>. In the end of December I lost a coat from my cow-house, which was broken open - I did not see the coat again till the 21st of June - the prisoner was in our neighbourhood at the time I lost it - I had occasionally employed him.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320705-284-person2318">
                  JOHN 
                  GREGORY JACKSON
               <interp inst="t18320705-284-person2318" type="surname" value="GREGORY JACKSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320705-284-person2318" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320705-284-person2318" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a pawnbroker, and live at Hounslow. I have a blue great-coat, which I took in from Smith, on the 7th of January.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. DONNE. Q. What is Smith? A. A labouring woman - I asked who she brought it for; she said John Brown.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320705-284-person2319">
                  ELIZABETH 
                  SMITH
               <interp inst="t18320705-284-person2319" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320705-284-person2319" type="given" value="ELIZABETH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320705-284-person2319" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a labouring woman. I pawned the coat - I was going up the town, and met the prisoner with 
               <persName id="t18320705-284-person2320">
                  Thomas 
                  Flicker
               <interp inst="t18320705-284-person2320" type="surname" value="Flicker"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320705-284-person2320" type="given" value="Thomas"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320705-284-person2320" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             - he was a soldier; he deserted, and was taken again, and is now in Ireland; the prisoner asked me to pawn the coat; I told him I never did such a thing, but as I knew Flicker I would - the prisoner had been carrying the coat - he gave it to Flicker, who gave it to me- he told me to ask 8s. for it, and I got 6s. - I pawned it in the name of John Brown, as I was told.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. Who first spoke to you? A. Flicker did - the prisoner asked him to ask me - I gave the money to the prisoner, who put it into his right hand pocket, and the duplicate - he thanked me, and they said good day- I had not seen the prisoner before; but I knew Flicker.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320705-284-person2321">
                  ROBERT 
                  PARNHAM
               <interp inst="t18320705-284-person2321" type="surname" value="PARNHAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320705-284-person2321" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320705-284-person2321" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . On the 4th of June, at half-past ten o'clock, the prosecutor gave Smith in charge; she told me where she got the coat, and I took the prisoner from her description.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. She said she gave the money to Flicker, and he gave it to me, because he had holes in his pocket.</p>
               <p>SMITH. No; he never touched it.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18320705-284-verdict1490" type="verdictDescription">
